This paper deals with the issue of fairness in automated decision-making, which is a topic that falls under the sub-fields of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of causal inference and constrained optimization also suggests that the paper may be relevant to the sub-fields of cybernetics (cs.CY) and security and privacy (cs.CR). Finally, the use of real criminal justice data suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-field of social and information networks (cs.SI).
